## Basic Text Elements

### Headings and Visual Hierarchy

Headings structure your presentation and guide the reader's attention:

# Heading Level 1 (H1) - Main titles only
## Heading Level 2 (H2) - Main sections
### Heading Level 3 (H3) - Subsections
#### Heading Level 4 (H4) - Specific details
##### Heading Level 5 (H5) - Minor elements
###### Heading Level 6 (H6) - Notes and clarifications

### Paragraphs and Spacing

Well-structured paragraphs make reading and comprehension easier. Each paragraph should contain a single, clearly defined central idea.

A separate paragraph creates a visual pause that lets the reader process the information before moving on to the next concept.

Spacing between paragraphs is crucial for readability — too little makes the text feel cramped, too much makes it feel disjointed.

---

## Inline Formatting: Emphasis and Highlights

### Fundamental Styles

- **Bold text** for critical information and key concepts
- *Italic text* for subtle emphasis and technical terms
- `Inline code` for commands, variables, and technical references
- ==Highlighted text== for information that should stand out visually
- ~~Strikethrough text~~ to show changes, updates, or outdated information

### Advanced Formatting Combinations

- **_Bold and italic combined_** for maximum emphasis
- ***Alternative for bold-italic*** with triple asterisk
- `**Bold code**` (formatting inside code)
- **Important text with an [embedded link](https://example.com)**
- *Italic with `inline code`* for technical references
- ==**Highlighted bold**== for critical alerts

### Links and References

**Basic links:**
- [Simple link](https://slidelang.com)
- [Link with title](https://docs.slidelang.com "Official documentation")
- [Contact email](mailto:support@slidelang.com)
- [Phone](tel:+1-555-123-4567)

**Formatted links:**
- **[Important link in bold](https://critical-link.com)**
- *[Subtle link in italics](https://subtle-link.com)*
- [`Technical link`](https://api.docs.com) for code documentation

**Reference links:**
This text includes a [reference link][1] that's defined at the end.
We can also use [multiple references][ref2] in the same paragraph.

[1]: https://example.com "First reference link"
[ref2]: https://another-example.com "Second reference link"

